        <!-- Introduction -->
        <section id="introduction" class="content-section">
          <h2>Introduction to Main Sequence Stars</h2>
          <p>Main sequence stars form the backbone of the universe. They are the "normal" stars—the vast majority of stars you see in the night sky are main sequence stars steadily converting hydrogen to helium through nuclear fusion. This phase represents the longest period in a star's life, a time of stability and equilibrium that can last from millions to trillions of years depending on the star's mass.</p>

          <p>The term "main sequence" comes from early 20th-century astronomers Ejnar Hertzsprung and Henry Norris Russell, who independently discovered that when you plot stars by their luminosity and temperature, most fall along a diagonal band. This "main sequence" wasn't just a statistical curiosity—it revealed fundamental physics about how stars work and evolve.</p>

          <p>What unites all main sequence stars is that they're all doing the same thing: fusing hydrogen into helium in their cores. This nuclear fusion releases tremendous energy that counteracts gravity, preventing the star from collapsing. The balance between gravitational pressure inward and radiation pressure outward creates a stable star that can shine steadily for billions of years.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Physical Characteristics -->
        <section id="characteristics" class="content-section">
          <h2>Physical Characteristics</h2>
          <p>Main sequence stars exhibit an enormous range of physical properties. At one extreme are red dwarfs—cool, dim stars with only 8% of the Sun's mass. At the other extreme are massive O-type stars with 100+ times the Sun's mass, blazing hot and incredibly luminous.</p>

          <div class="info-box glass">
            <h3>Main Sequence Range</h3>
            <ul>
