              <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> 2,500 K (M-type) to 50,000 K (O-type)</li>
              <li><strong>Luminosity:</strong> 0.0001 to 1,000,000 times the Sun</li>
              <li><strong>Radius:</strong> 0.1 to 25 solar radii</li>
              <li><strong>Lifetime:</strong> 10 million to 10 trillion years</li>
              <li><strong>Color:</strong> Red → Orange → Yellow → White → Blue</li>
              <li><strong>Main Sequence Duration:</strong> Mass-dependent (lower mass = longer life)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <h3>The Mass-Luminosity Relationship</h3>
          <p>One of the most important relationships in stellar physics is that luminosity increases dramatically with mass. A star twice as massive as the Sun isn't just twice as bright—it's about 11 times brighter. A star ten times more massive is over 3,000 times more luminous. This relationship follows approximately L ∝ M³·⁵, where L is luminosity and M is mass.</p>

          <p>This mass-luminosity relationship has profound consequences. More massive stars burn through their hydrogen fuel much faster despite having more fuel to begin with. A star with 20 times the Sun's mass has 20 times more hydrogen, but it burns that fuel at a rate 20,000 times faster, exhausting it in just 10 million years compared to the Sun's 10 billion year lifespan.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Formation -->
        <section id="formation" class="content-section">
          <h2>Formation of Main Sequence Stars</h2>
          <p>Main sequence stars form from the collapse of giant molecular clouds—vast regions of cold gas and dust in space. When a region of the cloud becomes dense enough, gravity causes it to collapse further, creating a protostar. As the protostar continues to collapse, its core temperature and pressure increase.</p>

          <h3>From Protostar to Main Sequence</h3>
          <p>The journey from cloud collapse to main sequence star typically takes 10-50 million years for Sun-like stars. During this time, the protostar goes through several phases: it contracts and heats up, begins to glow from the heat of gravitational compression, and eventually reaches the critical temperature of about 10 million Kelvin in its core.</p>

          <p>At this temperature, hydrogen nuclei move fast enough to overcome their mutual electrostatic repulsion and fuse together, forming helium and releasing enormous amounts of energy. This marks the star's arrival on the main sequence—it has "turned on" and will remain stable for the rest of its hydrogen-burning lifetime.</p>

          <h3>The Mass Threshold</h3>
          <p>Not all collapsing clouds become main sequence stars. Objects below about 0.08 solar masses (roughly 80 Jupiter masses) never get hot enough in their cores to sustain hydrogen fusion. These are brown dwarfs—"failed stars" that glow dimly from leftover heat but never achieve true stellar status. The 0.08 solar mass threshold represents the minimum mass for a main sequence star.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Lifecycle Stage -->
        <section id="lifecycle" class="content-section">
          <h2>Main Sequence as a Lifecycle Stage</h2>
          <p>The main sequence is not a type of star but rather a stage in stellar evolution—specifically, the hydrogen-burning phase. Stars spend more time on the main sequence than in any other phase of their lives, which is why most stars we observe are main sequence stars.</p>

          <h3>Stellar Lifetimes</h3>
          <p>A star's mass determines how long it remains on the main sequence:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Massive Stars (10+ solar masses):</strong> 10-100 million years on the main sequence. These stars burn hot and bright, exhausting their hydrogen quickly.</li>
            <li><strong>Sun-like Stars (0.8-1.2 solar masses):</strong> 8-15 billion years on the main sequence. The Sun will spend about 10 billion years total in this phase.</li>
            <li><strong>Red Dwarfs (0.08-0.5 solar masses):</strong> 1-10 trillion years on the main sequence. The smallest red dwarfs will outlive the current universe many times over.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>What Comes After</h3>
          <p>When a star exhausts the hydrogen in its core, it leaves the main sequence. For Sun-like stars, this means expanding into a <a href="/atlas/stars/red-giants/">red giant</a>, eventually shedding outer layers to form a planetary nebula and leaving behind a <a href="/atlas/stars/white-dwarfs/">white dwarf</a>. Massive stars become <a href="/atlas/stars/supergiants/">supergiants</a> and may explode as supernovae, leaving behind <a href="/atlas/stars/neutron-stars/">neutron stars</a> or <a href="/atlas/stars/black-holes/">black holes</a>.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Composition -->
        <section id="composition" class="content-section">
          <h2>Composition and Nuclear Processes</h2>
          <p>Main sequence stars are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium, the two lightest and most abundant elements in the universe. A typical composition is about 73% hydrogen, 25% helium, and 2% heavier elements (collectively called "metals" in astronomy, even though they include non-metallic elements like oxygen and carbon).</p>

          <h3>The Proton-Proton Chain</h3>
          <p>In stars like the Sun and smaller, hydrogen fusion occurs via the proton-proton chain reaction. This process takes four hydrogen nuclei (protons) and combines them into one helium nucleus, releasing energy in the form of gamma rays and neutrinos. The process occurs in several steps and requires temperatures of at least 10 million Kelvin.</p>

          <p>Every second, the Sun converts about 600 million tons of hydrogen into helium. About 4 million tons of matter are converted directly into energy via Einstein's famous E=mc² equation. This tiny loss of mass releases enough energy to power the Sun's tremendous luminosity.</p>

          <h3>The CNO Cycle</h3>
          <p>In more massive and hotter stars (above about 1.3 solar masses), hydrogen fusion predominantly occurs through the CNO (Carbon-Nitrogen-Oxygen) cycle. This process uses carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen as catalysts to convert hydrogen to helium. The CNO cycle is far more temperature-sensitive than the proton-proton chain, which is why it dominates in hotter, more massive stars.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- H-R Diagram -->
        <section id="hr-diagram" class="content-section">
          <h2>The Hertzsprung-Russell Diagram</h2>
          <p>The Hertzsprung-Russell (H-R) diagram is one of the most important tools in astronomy. It's a scatter plot that charts stars according to their luminosity (or absolute magnitude) on the vertical axis and their temperature (or spectral type/color) on the horizontal axis.</p>

          <h3>The Main Sequence Band</h3>
          <p>When thousands of stars are plotted on the H-R diagram, they don't scatter randomly. Instead, about 90% fall along a diagonal band running from the upper left (hot, luminous blue stars) to the lower right (cool, dim red stars). This band is the main sequence, and its existence was a major breakthrough in understanding stellar physics.</p>

          <p>The main sequence isn't arbitrary—it represents the relationship between a star's mass, temperature, and luminosity during the hydrogen-burning phase. More massive stars are both hotter and more luminous, which is why they appear in the upper left. Less massive stars are cooler and dimmer, appearing in the lower right.</p>

          <h3>Other Regions of the H-R Diagram</h3>
          <p>Stars not on the main sequence occupy other regions: <a href="/atlas/stars/red-giants/">red giants</a> and <a href="/atlas/stars/supergiants/">supergiants</a> in the upper right (cool but luminous), and <a href="/atlas/stars/white-dwarfs/">white dwarfs</a> in the lower left (hot but dim). The H-R diagram thus provides a snapshot of stellar evolution—we can see stars at different stages of their lives.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Stellar Classification -->
        <section id="classification" class="content-section">
          <h2>Stellar Classification</h2>
          <p>Astronomers classify main sequence stars using the Morgan-Keenan (MK) system, which categorizes stars by their spectral type (temperature) and luminosity class. Main sequence stars are luminosity class V (Roman numeral five), also called "dwarf" stars.</p>

          <h3>Spectral Types</h3>
          <p>Spectral types range from hottest to coolest: O, B, A, F, G, K, M. Each type is further divided into subtypes 0-9. The Sun, for example, is a G2V star—a main sequence star (V) of spectral type G, subtype 2.</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>O-type (30,000-50,000 K):</strong> Extremely hot, blue stars. Rare and short-lived, they represent less than 0.001% of main sequence stars.</li>
            <li><strong>B-type (10,000-30,000 K):</strong> Hot, blue-white stars like Rigel and Spica. Still rare, comprising about 0.1% of stars.</li>
            <li><strong>A-type (7,500-10,000 K):</strong> White stars like Sirius A and Vega. About 0.6% of all stars.</li>
            <li><strong>F-type (6,000-7,500 K):</strong> Yellow-white stars like Procyon A. About 3% of stars.</li>
            <li><strong>G-type (5,200-6,000 K):</strong> Yellow stars like the Sun and Alpha Centauri A. About 7.6% of stars.</li>
            <li><strong>K-type (3,700-5,200 K):</strong> Orange stars like Epsilon Eridani. About 12% of stars.</li>
            <li><strong>M-type (2,400-3,700 K):</strong> Red dwarfs like Proxima Centauri. These are by far the most common, representing about 76% of all main sequence stars.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>The fact that cool red dwarfs vastly outnumber all other types is remarkable. Despite being the most common stars in the universe, red dwarfs are so dim that not a single one is visible to the naked eye from Earth—all the stars you can see unaided are either more massive main sequence stars or evolved giants.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Notable Examples -->
        <section id="examples" class="content-section">
          <h2>Notable Main Sequence Stars</h2>
          <p>Many of the most familiar stars in the night sky are main sequence stars. Here are some notable examples across the spectral range:</p>

          <h3>The Sun (G2V)</h3>
          <p>Our home star is a perfectly ordinary G-type main sequence star about 4.6 billion years old and halfway through its main sequence lifetime. With a surface temperature of 5,778 K, the Sun serves as the reference point for stellar measurements—other stars are often described in terms of solar masses, solar radii, and solar luminosities.</p>

          <h3>Sirius A (A1V)</h3>
          <p>The brightest star in Earth's night sky, Sirius A is a white main sequence star about twice the Sun's mass and 25 times more luminous. At just 8.6 light-years away, its proximity combined with its high intrinsic brightness makes it the dominant star in our night sky. Sirius A has a white dwarf companion, Sirius B.</p>

          <h3>Alpha Centauri A (G2V)</h3>
          <p>Remarkably similar to the Sun, Alpha Centauri A is part of the closest star system to Earth at just 4.37 light-years away. It's slightly more massive and luminous than the Sun and is part of a triple system including Alpha Centauri B (K1V) and Proxima Centauri (M5.5V).</p>

          <h3>Proxima Centauri (M5.5V)</h3>
          <p>The closest star to Earth after the Sun, Proxima Centauri is a red dwarf just 4.24 light-years away. Despite its proximity, it's too dim to see with the naked eye. With only 12% of the Sun's mass and 0.17% of its luminosity, Proxima represents the most common type of star in the galaxy. It will remain on the main sequence for trillions of years.</p>

          <h3>Vega (A0V)</h3>
          <p>A brilliant white star in the constellation Lyra, Vega is about 2.1 times the Sun's mass and 40 times more luminous. It's relatively young—about 450 million years old—and will only spend about 1 billion years total on the main sequence. Vega was the north star about 14,000 years ago and will be again in about 12,000 years.</p>

          <h3>Tau Ceti (G8V)</h3>
          <p>Located just 11.9 light-years away, Tau Ceti is a G-type star similar to but slightly smaller and cooler than the Sun. It's notable for having at least four confirmed planets in its habitable zone, making it a target of interest in the search for potentially habitable worlds.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Observation -->
        <section id="observation" class="content-section">
          <h2>Observing Main Sequence Stars</h2>
          <p>Main sequence stars are the easiest stars to observe because they're by far the most numerous. Every star visible to the naked eye (except a few giants and supergiants) is either a main sequence star or has recently evolved off the main sequence.</p>

          <h3>What Telescopes Reveal</h3>
          <p>Through telescopes, astronomers can measure key properties of main sequence stars: their spectra (revealing temperature and composition), luminosity, and in some cases their radii. For nearby stars, parallax measurements give precise distances, allowing calculation of absolute luminosity. Binary systems are particularly valuable because they allow direct mass measurements.</p>

          <h3>Professional Observations</h3>
          <p>Modern professional telescopes and space observatories study main sequence stars to understand stellar physics, stellar evolution, and planet formation. The Gaia space telescope has measured precise distances and properties for over a billion stars, most of them main sequence. NASA's TESS mission searches main sequence stars for transiting exoplanets.</p>

          <h3>Amateur Observations</h3>
          <p>Amateur astronomers can observe thousands of main sequence stars and easily distinguish their colors. Binoculars or small telescopes reveal color contrasts in <a href="/atlas/stars/binary-systems/">binary systems</a> like Albireo (gold and blue stars). Spectroscopy, accessible to advanced amateurs, can reveal a star's spectral type and physical properties.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Interesting Facts -->
        <section id="fun-facts" class="content-section">
          <h2>Interesting Facts About Main Sequence Stars</h2>
          <p>Main sequence stars reveal fascinating physics and surprising statistics about the universe.</p>

          <ul class="facts-list">
            <li><strong>Red Dwarfs Everywhere:</strong> About 76% of all main sequence stars are red dwarfs (M-type), yet not a single one is visible to the naked eye from Earth. All the stars you can see unaided are more massive, less common types.</li>

            <li><strong>Never-Dying Stars:</strong> The smallest red dwarfs will remain on the main sequence for 1-10 trillion years—far longer than the universe's current age of 13.8 billion years. No red dwarf has ever evolved off the main sequence since the universe began.</li>

            <li><strong>The Massive Burn Fast:</strong> A star 20 times the Sun's mass has 20 times more fuel but burns it 20,000 times faster, exhausting its hydrogen in just 10 million years compared to the Sun's 10-billion-year lifetime.</li>

            <li><strong>Stellar Alchemy:</strong> Every second, the Sun converts 600 million tons of hydrogen into helium, with 4 million tons converted directly into energy. In its 10-billion-year main sequence lifetime, it will convert only 0.7% of its mass into energy.</li>

            <li><strong>The 90% Rule:</strong> About 90% of all stars are currently on the main sequence. This isn't because it's the most common stellar stage—it's because stars spend most of their lives there.</li>

            <li><strong>Perfect Balance:</strong> Main sequence stars exist in perfect hydrostatic equilibrium—gravity pulling inward exactly balanced by radiation pressure pushing outward. Any slight imbalance triggers changes that restore equilibrium, making main sequence stars remarkably stable.</li>

            <li><strong>Color Indicates Age and Mass:</strong> Blue main sequence stars are both the most massive and the youngest—they burn out quickly. Red main sequence stars are both the least massive and potentially the oldest stars in existence.</li>

            <li><strong>The Sun is Middle-Aged:</strong> At 4.6 billion years old, the Sun is about halfway through its 10-billion-year main sequence lifetime. In another 5 billion years, it will exhaust its core hydrogen and begin evolving into a red giant.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

